---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout title="Kala Sarpa Bali | Annual Rahu-Ketu Ritual | Nagayakshi Temple">

  <section class="pooja-hero">
    <div class="pooja-hero-overlay"></div>
    <div class="pooja-hero-content">
      <span class="pooja-badge">Annual Ceremony</span>
      <h1>Kala Sarpa Bali</h1>
      <p class="pooja-tagline">The most powerful annual ritual to pacify the Kala Sarpa Dosha and unlock your destiny</p>
      <div class="pooja-quick-info">
        <div class="quick-info-item">
          <span class="info-label">Frequency</span>
          <span class="info-value">Annual</span>
        </div>
        <div class="quick-info-item">
          <span class="info-label">Duration</span>
          <span class="info-value">Full Day</span>
        </div>
        <div class="quick-info-item">
          <span class="info-label">Starting From</span>
          <span class="info-value">&#8377;10,000</span>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="hero-ctas">
        <a href="#booking" class="btn-primary-gold">Book This Bali</a>
        <a href="#details" class="btn-secondary-outline">Learn More</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- What Is This Ritual -->
  <section class="pooja-section" id="details">
    <div class="pooja-container">
      <div class="section-header">
        <h2>What is Kala Sarpa Bali?</h2>
      </div>
      <div class="content-grid">
        <div class="content-main">
          <p class="intro-text">
            Kala Sarpa Bali is the most intensive and comprehensive annual ritual offered at
            Sree Pulikkal Vishwanagayakshi Temple. Performed for those with Kala Sarpa Dosha
            in their horoscope&#8212;where all seven planets are hemmed between Rahu and Ketu&#8212;
            this full-day ceremony combines fire oblations, serpent worship, ancestral appeasement,
            and Naga deity blessings to break the cosmic cycle of karmic delays and unlock the
            devotee&#8217;s blocked destiny. Participation is strictly limited to 25 devotees
            per annual ceremony.
          </p>
          <h3>The Three-Phase Ceremony</h3>
          <p>Kala Sarpa Bali unfolds in three sequential ritual phases across a full day:</p>
          <div class="variant-cards">
            <div class="variant-card">
              <h4>1. Rahu-Ketu Tharpanam</h4>
              <p>
                <strong>Morning phase:</strong> Ancestral water offerings and mantra japa to
                Rahu and Ketu, individually addressing each planet&#8217;s placement in the
                horoscope and pacifying their karmic demands
              </p>
            </div>
            <div class="variant-card">
              <h4>2. Sarpa Bali Homam</h4>
              <p>
                <strong>Midday phase:</strong> The central fire ritual with 1,008 ahutis
                (offerings) into a consecrated fire, accompanied by the chanting of the
                Sarpa Sukta and Naga Stotra for comprehensive dosha removal
              </p>
            </div>
            <div class="variant-card">
              <h4>3. Navagraha Naga Pooja</h4>
              <p>
                <strong>Evening phase:</strong> Individual worship of the nine planetary serpent
                deities, closing the ritual by establishing harmony between all planets and
                releasing the Kala Sarpa blockage
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="content-sidebar">
          <div class="info-box">
            <h4>Quick Facts</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Once-a-year intensive ceremony</li>
              <li>Maximum 25 participants</li>
              <li>Full day from sunrise to sunset</li>
              <li>Led by Ambotti Thampuran</li>
              <li>Most powerful dosha remedy at this temple</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="info-box highlight">
            <h4>Best For</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Confirmed Kala Sarpa Dosha</li>
              <li>Repeated life setbacks</li>
              <li>Blocked career &amp; progress</li>
              <li>Chronic health issues</li>
              <li>Delayed marriage &amp; progeny</li>
              <li>Ancestral karmic burdens</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Traditional Basis -->
  <section class="tradition-section">
    <div class="pooja-container">
      <div class="section-header">
        <span class="section-label">Sacred Origins</span>
        <h2>The Tradition of Kala Sarpa Bali</h2>
      </div>
      <div class="tradition-story">
        <div class="story-image">
          <img src="/images/Noorum%20Paalum.jpeg" alt="Kala Sarpa Bali ritual">
        </div>
        <div class="story-content">
          <h3>The Cosmic Serpent Cycle</h3>
          <p>
            Kala Sarpa Dosha arises when all seven planets&#8212;Sun, Moon, Mars, Mercury,
            Jupiter, Venus, and Saturn&#8212;are positioned between Rahu and Ketu in the
            birth horoscope. In Vedic Jyotish, this configuration is considered one of the
            most significant karmic indicators, signaling that the soul carries unresolved
            debts from past lives related to serpents, ancestors, or broken vows.
          </p>
          <p>
            The Kala Sarpa Bali at this temple draws its authority from the <strong>Parashurama
            tradition</strong> of Kerala, where the pacification of Rahu and Ketu is performed
            through the intermediary of the Naga deities who are believed to govern these
            shadow planets. This direct channel to the serpent powers makes the ritual
            uniquely effective for breaking the Kala Sarpa cycle.
          </p>
          <div class="scripture-quote">
            <p>
              &#8220;Where all the planets between Rahu and Ketu are contained, the native
              faces great obstacles. But through the propitiation of the Nagas&#8212;who are
              the very body of Rahu and Ketu&#8212;these obstacles are dissolved and destiny
              is restored.&#8221;
            </p>
            <span class="quote-attribution">&#8212; Parasara Hora Sastra, Chapter on Naga Remedies</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="tradition-variants">
        <h3>The Twelve Types of Kala Sarpa Dosha</h3>
        <div class="variant-detail">
          <h4>Ananta, Kulika, Vasuki &amp; Others</h4>
          <p>
            There are twelve recognized forms of Kala Sarpa Dosha, each named after a
            different cosmic serpent (Ananta, Kulika, Vasuki, Shankhapala, Padma, Mahapadma,
            Takshaka, Karkotaka, Shankhanaada, Ghatak, Vishakta, and Sheshanaag), depending
            on which house Rahu occupies. Each form has slightly different effects and
            requires specific modifications to the standard Bali ritual.
          </p>
          <p>
            Ambotti Thampuran analyzes the devotee&#8217;s horoscope before the ceremony
            to identify the specific type of Kala Sarpa Dosha and tailor the ritual
            accordingly, ensuring that the correct serpent deity is invoked for maximum
            remedial effect.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="variant-detail">
          <h4>Why Annual Repetition Matters</h4>
          <p>
            Kala Sarpa Dosha is a karmic pattern that spans many lifetimes. A single Bali
            ceremony creates significant relief and opens blocked pathways, but the full
            dissolution of the dosha typically requires the ceremony to be performed annually
            for <strong>3, 7, or 12 consecutive years</strong>, depending on the severity
            of the placement. Each annual ceremony deepens the remedial effect and accelerates
            the karmic resolution.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Who Should Perform -->
  <section class="pooja-section audience-section">
    <div class="pooja-container">
      <div class="section-header">
        <h2>Who Should Perform Kala Sarpa Bali?</h2>
        <p class="section-intro">This most powerful annual ceremony is especially beneficial for those in these situations</p>
      </div>
      <div class="audience-grid">
        <div class="audience-card">
          <div class="audience-icon">
            <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5"><circle cx="12" cy="12" r="10"/><line x1="12" y1="8" x2="12" y2="12"/><line x1="12" y1="16" x2="12.01" y2="16"/></svg>
          </div>
          <h3>Kala Sarpa Dosha Confirmed</h3>
          <p>Individuals whose horoscope has been verified by a Jyotish expert to contain one of the twelve forms of Kala Sarpa Dosha.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="audience-card">
          <div class="audience-icon">
            <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5"><path d="M12 2v20M17 5H9.5a3.5 3.5 0 0 0 0 7h5a3.5 3.5 0 0 1 0 7H6"/></svg>
          </div>
          <h3>Persistent Financial Blocks</h3>
          <p>Those who work diligently but cannot sustain financial growth, with wealth earned quickly dissipating without explanation.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="audience-card">
          <div class="audience-icon">
            <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5"><path d="M20.84 4.61a5.5 5.5 0 0 0-7.78 0L12 5.67l-1.06-1.06a5.5 5.5 0 0 0-7.78 7.78l1.06 1.06L12 21.23l7.78-7.78 1.06-1.06a5.5 5.5 0 0 0 0-7.78z"/></svg>
          </div>
          <h3>Delayed Marriage</h3>
          <p>Individuals past typical marriage age facing unexplained rejections or broken engagements despite being suitable in all respects.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="audience-card">
          <div class="audience-icon">
            <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5"><path d="M17 21v-2a4 4 0 0 0-4-4H5a4 4 0 0 0-4 4v2"/><circle cx="9" cy="7" r="4"/><path d="M23 21v-2a4 4 0 0 0-3-3.87"/><path d="M16 3.13a4 4 0 0 1 0 7.75"/></svg>
          </div>
          <h3>Progeny Difficulties</h3>
          <p>Couples facing infertility, repeated miscarriages, or inability to conceive despite medical clearance on both sides.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="audience-card">
          <div class="audience-icon">
            <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5"><path d="M22 12h-4l-3 9L9 3l-3 9H2"/></svg>
          </div>
          <h3>Sade Sati &amp; Rahu Dasha</h3>
          <p>Those currently running Rahu Mahadasha, Ketu Dasha, or Saturn&#8217;s Sade Sati who face extreme turbulence and setbacks.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="audience-card">
          <div class="audience-icon">
            <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5"><path d="M3 9l9-7 9 7v11a2 2 0 0 1-2 2H5a2 2 0 0 1-2-2z"/><polyline points="9 22 9 12 15 12 15 22"/></svg>
          </div>
          <h3>Ancestral Karmic Debt</h3>
          <p>Those from families where serpent worship was practiced historically but discontinued, causing generational patterns of suffering.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="audience-card">
          <div class="audience-icon">
            <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5"><path d="M12 22v-6M12 8v8M7 13s1.5-2 5-2 5 2 5 2M7 18s1.5-2 5-2 5 2 5 2M12 8c-2.5 0-4-2.5-4-5 0-2 1.5-3 4-3s4 1 4 3c0 2.5-1.5 5-4 5z"/></svg>
          </div>
          <h3>Career Plateau</h3>
          <p>Talented professionals whose careers inexplicably stall just before major breakthroughs, with opportunities repeatedly falling through at the final stage.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="audience-card">
          <div class="audience-icon">
            <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5"><path d="M17 8h1a4 4 0 1 1 0 8h-1M3 8h14v9a4 4 0 0 1-4 4H7a4 4 0 0 1-4-4V8z"/></svg>
          </div>
          <h3>Recurring Nightmares</h3>
          <p>Individuals plagued by recurring nightmares involving serpents, water, or ancestors&#8212;a classical sign of unresolved Naga and Rahu-Ketu karma.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Pricing -->
  <section class="pricing-section">
    <div class="pooja-container">
      <div class="section-header">
        <h2>Ceremony Pricing</h2>
      </div>
      <div class="pricing-grid single-price">
        <div class="price-card featured">
          <div class="price-badge">Annual Ceremony</div>
          <div class="price-header">
            <h3>Kala Sarpa Bali</h3>
            <div class="price-amount">
              <span class="currency">&#8377;</span>
              <span class="amount">10,000</span>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="price-features">
            <h4>Includes:</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Full-day ceremony (sunrise to sunset)</li>
              <li>Rahu-Ketu Tharpanam (morning)</li>
              <li>Sarpa Bali Homam with 1,008 ahutis (midday)</li>
              <li>Navagraha Naga Pooja (evening)</li>
              <li>Personal horoscope consultation</li>
              <li>Individual sankalpa &amp; name inclusion</li>
              <li>Sacred ash &amp; full prasadam package</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <a href="#booking" class="price-cta">Book Now</a>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="pricing-note">
        <p><strong>Important:</strong> Participation is strictly limited to <strong>25 devotees per annual ceremony</strong>.
        Early registration is essential to secure a slot. Prasadam shipping charges apply for locations outside Kerala.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- FAQ -->
  <section class="faq-section">
    <div class="pooja-container">
      <div class="section-header">
        <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-list">
        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary>How do I confirm if I have Kala Sarpa Dosha?</summary>
          <p>
            Kala Sarpa Dosha is confirmed by checking whether all seven planets in your
            birth chart (Sun, Moon, Mars, Mercury, Jupiter, Venus, Saturn) are positioned
            between Rahu and Ketu. You can verify this with a Jyotish expert using your
            exact date, time, and place of birth. Contact us with these details and
            Ambotti Thampuran can also advise.
          </p>
        </details>
        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary>How many times should I perform Kala Sarpa Bali?</summary>
          <p>
            Depending on the severity of the dosha: mild cases show significant improvement
            after 1&#8211;3 annual ceremonies. Moderate to severe Kala Sarpa Dosha
            typically requires 7 annual repetitions for full resolution. The most deeply
            rooted karmic forms may require 12 consecutive years of annual ceremony.
            Ambotti Thampuran can recommend the appropriate course after reviewing your
            horoscope.
          </p>
        </details>
        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary>Why is participation limited to 25 devotees?</summary>
          <p>
            Kala Sarpa Bali is an all-day, highly intensive ceremony requiring the priest&#8217;s
            complete attention for each participant&#8217;s sankalpa and individual ritual
            elements. Exceeding 25 participants would compromise the depth and efficacy of
            the ritual for each individual. This limit ensures every devotee receives the
            full power of the ceremony.
          </p>
        </details>
        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary>Can I attend if I cannot be present in person?</summary>
          <p>
            Yes. Your participation can be registered by proxy&#8212;the priest takes your
            name, nakshatra, gotra, and intention into the sankalpa and performs the full
            ritual on your behalf. Prasadam (sacred ash, turmeric from the ritual, and
            blessed items) will be dispatched to you after the ceremony. In-person attendance
            is always more powerful, but the proxy method is fully accepted in this tradition.
          </p>
        </details>
        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary>What is the difference between Kala Sarpa Bali and Navagraha Homam?</summary>
          <p>
            Navagraha Homam addresses all nine planets generally and provides broad planetary
            harmony. Kala Sarpa Bali is specifically and exclusively for those with the
            Kala Sarpa Dosha configuration and works directly through the Naga deities who
            govern Rahu and Ketu. Many devotees with Kala Sarpa Dosha perform both&#8212;
            quarterly Navagraha Homam for ongoing planetary balance and the annual Kala Sarpa
            Bali for the core dosha remedy.
          </p>
        </details>
        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary>When is the annual ceremony typically held?</summary>
          <p>
            The annual Kala Sarpa Bali is scheduled on the most auspicious Naga Nakshathra
            date of the year&#8212;typically on or around Ayilyam in the month of Karkidakam
            (July&#8211;August), considered the most potent time for serpent deity worship.
            Contact us for the confirmed date of the upcoming ceremony and to register your
            slot before the 25-participant limit is reached.
          </p>
        </details>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Booking CTA -->
  <section class="booking-cta-section" id="booking">
    <div class="booking-cta-container">
      <h2>Reserve Your Slot</h2>
      <p>
        <strong>Limited to 25 participants</strong> &#8212; slots fill quickly<br>
        Contact us early to confirm your place in the annual ceremony
      </p>
      <div class="booking-cta-buttons">
        <a href="/register" class="btn-primary-gold btn-large">Book Online Now</a>
        <a href="tel:+919946373522" class="btn-secondary-outline">Call: +91 9946373522</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

</Layout>

<style>
/* Hero */
.pooja-hero {
  position: relative;
  min-height: 70vh;
  display: flex;
  align-items: center;
  justify-content: center;
  background:
    linear-gradient(rgba(82, 14, 9, 0.75), rgba(82, 14, 9, 0.9)),
    url('/images/Payasa%20Bali.jpg') center/cover;
  padding: 8rem 2rem 4rem;
  text-align: center;
}

.pooja-hero-overlay {
  position: absolute;
  inset: 0;
  background: radial-gradient(circle at 50% 50%, rgba(212, 165, 116, 0.12) 0%, transparent 60%);
}

.pooja-hero-content {
  max-width: 900px;
  position: relative;
  z-index: 10;
}

.pooja-badge {
  display: inline-block;
  background: var(--laterite-red);
  color: white;
  padding: 0.5rem 1.5rem;
  border-radius: 30px;
  font-size: 0.9rem;
  font-weight: 600;
  text-transform: uppercase;
  letter-spacing: 2px;
  margin-bottom: 1.5rem;
}

.pooja-hero h1 {
  font-family: 'Cormorant Garamond', serif;
  font-size: 4.2rem;
  font-weight: 700;
  color: white;
  margin-bottom: 1rem;
  text-shadow: 0 2px 20px rgba(0,0,0,0.5);
}

.pooja-tagline {
  font-size: 1.35rem;
  color: var(--bg-alt);
  margin-bottom: 3rem;
}

.pooja-quick-info {
  display: flex;
  gap: 2rem;
  justify-content: center;
  flex-wrap: wrap;
  margin-bottom: 3rem;
  padding: 1.8rem 2rem;
  background: rgba(255,255,255,0.1);
  backdrop-filter: blur(10px);
  border-radius: 12px;
  border: 1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.2);
}

.quick-info-item {
  display: flex;
  flex-direction: column;
  align-items: center;
  gap: 0.4rem;
}

.info-label {
  font-size: 0.8rem;
  color: #ffd285;
  text-transform: uppercase;
  letter-spacing: 1px;
}

.info-value {
  font-size: 1.15rem;
  color: white;
  font-weight: 600;
}

.hero-ctas {
  display: flex;
  gap: 1.5rem;
  justify-content: center;
  flex-wrap: wrap;
}

/* Sections */
.pooja-section {
  padding: 5rem 2rem;
  background: var(--bg-base);
}

.pooja-section.audience-section {
  background: var(--bg-alt);
}

.pooja-container {
  max-width: 1200px;
  margin: 0 auto;
}

/* Content grid */
.content-grid {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: 2fr 1fr;
  gap: 3rem;
}

.content-main {
  font-size: 1.05rem;
  color: var(--text-muted);
  line-height: 1.9;
}

.intro-text {
  font-size: 1.15rem;
  color: var(--laterite-dark);
  line-height: 1.9;
  margin-bottom: 2rem;
}

.content-main h3 {
  font-family: 'Cormorant Garamond', serif;
  font-size: 1.9rem;
  font-weight: 600;
  color: var(--laterite-red);
  margin: 2.5rem 0 1.2rem;
}

.content-main p {
  margin-bottom: 1.2rem;
}

.variant-cards {
  display: flex;
  flex-direction: column;
  gap: 1.2rem;
  margin-top: 1.5rem;
}

.variant-card {
  background: var(--bg-alt);
  padding: 1.5rem;
  border-radius: 8px;
  border-left: 4px solid var(--gold);
}

.variant-card h4 {
  font-family: 'Cormorant Garamond', serif;
  font-size: 1.3rem;
  font-weight: 700;
  color: var(--laterite-red);
  margin-bottom: 0.8rem;
}

.variant-card p {
  font-size: 1rem;
  line-height: 1.7;
  margin: 0;
}

/* Sidebar */
.content-sidebar {
  display: flex;
  flex-direction: column;
  gap: 2rem;
}

.info-box {
  background: var(--bg-alt);
  padding: 1.8rem;
  border-radius: 10px;
  border: 2px solid #e8c9a0;
}

.info-box.highlight {
  background: var(--laterite-dark);
  border-color: var(--gold);
}

.info-box h4 {
  font-family: 'Cormorant Garamond', serif;
  font-size: 1.3rem;
  font-weight: 700;
  color: var(--laterite-red);
  margin-bottom: 1rem;
}

.info-box.highlight h4 {
  color: #ffd285;
}

.info-box ul {
  list-style: none;
  padding: 0;
}

.info-box li {
  padding: 0.5rem 0 0.5rem 1.5rem;
  position: relative;
  color: var(--text-muted);
  line-height: 1.6;
  border-bottom: 1px solid rgba(0,0,0,0.05);
}

.info-box.highlight li {
  color: var(--bg-alt);
  border-color: rgba(255,255,255,0.1);
}

.info-box li::before {
  content: '✓';
  position: absolute;
  left: 0;
  color: var(--laterite-red);
  font-weight: 700;
}

.info-box.highlight li::before {
  color: var(--gold);
}

/* Tradition section */
.tradition-section {
  padding: 5rem 2rem;
  background: var(--bg-alt);
}

.section-label {
  display: block;
  font-family: 'Source Serif 4', serif;
  font-size: 0.85rem;
  color: var(--saffron);
  text-transform: uppercase;
  letter-spacing: 3px;
  margin-bottom: 0.8rem;
  text-align: center;
}

.tradition-story {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: 420px 1fr;
  gap: 3rem;
  align-items: start;
  margin: 3rem 0;
}

.story-image img {
  width: 100%;
  border-radius: 12px;
  box-shadow: 0 12px 40px rgba(0,0,0,0.15);
  filter: sepia(0.15) brightness(0.95);
}

.story-content h3 {
  font-family: 'Cormorant Garamond', serif;
  font-size: 1.9rem;
  font-weight: 700;
  color: var(--laterite-red);
  margin-bottom: 1.2rem;
}

.story-content p {
  font-size: 1.05rem;
  color: var(--text-muted);
  line-height: 1.9;
  margin-bottom: 1.4rem;
}

.scripture-quote {
  background: var(--bg-base);
  padding: 1.8rem;
  border-radius: 10px;
  border-left: 4px solid var(--laterite-red);
  margin-top: 1.5rem;
}

.scripture-quote p {
  font-family: 'Cormorant Garamond', serif;
  font-size: 1.25rem;
  font-style: italic;
  color: var(--laterite-dark);
  line-height: 1.7;
  margin-bottom: 0.8rem;
}

.quote-attribution {
  font-size: 0.9rem;
  color: var(--text-muted);
}

.tradition-variants {
